tion_footnotes      = \n|elevation_m              = 180\n|elevation_ft             = 591\n|coordinates              = {{coord|35|57|20|N|95|22|41|W|region:US_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]s\n|postal_code              = 74467, 74477\n|area_code                = [[area codes 539 and 918|539/918]]\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 40-77850<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=http://factfinder.census.gov|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200212221153/http://factfinder.census.gov/main.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2020-02-12|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=American FactFinder}}</ref>\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 1099288<ref name=\"GR3\">{{cite web|url=http://geonames.usgs.gov|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=US Board on Geographic Names|publisher=[[United States Geological Survey]]|date=2007-10-25}}</ref>\n|website                  = [http://wagonerok.org/ Wagoner, Oklahoma]\n|footnotes                = \n|pop_est_as_of = 2018\n|pop_est_footnotes = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018CenPopScriptOnlyDirtyFixDoNotUse\"/>\n|population_est = 9061\n}}\n'''Wagoner''' is a city in [[Wagoner County, Oklahoma|Wagoner County]], [[Oklahoma]], United States. The population was 8,323 at the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]],<ref name=\"CensusViewer\">CensusViewer: Population of the City of Wagoner, Oklahoma. Retrieved March 16, 2012.[http://censusviewer.com/city/OK/Wagoner/2010]</ref> compared to 7,669 at the [[2000 United States Census|2000 census]]. It is the [[county seat]] of [[Wagoner County, Oklahoma|Wagoner County]].<ref name=\"GR6\">{{cite web|url=http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx|accessdate=2011-06-07|title=Find a County|publisher=National Association of Counties}}</ref> It became the first city incorporated in [[Indian Territory]] on January 4, 1896.<ref name = \"EOHC-Wagoner\">Williams, Shirle Lamb. ''Encyclopedia of Oklahoma History and Culture''. \"Wagoner\" Retrieved February 26, 2012.[http://digital.library.okstate.edu/encyclopedia/entries/W/WA002.html]</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{US Census population\n|1900= 2372\n|1910= 4018\n|1920= 3436\n|1930= 2994\n|1940= 3535\n|1950= 4395\n|1960= 4469\n|1970= 4959\n|1980= 6191\n|1990= 6894\n|2000= 7669\n|2010= 8323\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=9061\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018CenPopScriptOnlyDirtyFixDoNotUse\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=June 4, 2019}}</ref>\n|footnote=<ref name = \"EOHC-Wagoner\"/>\n}}\n\nWagoner is along the path of the [[Texas Road]] cattle trail,<ref>{{cite web |url = https://www.okhistory.org/publications/enc/entry.php?entry=TE023 | title= Texas Road | publisher=[[Oklahoma Historical Society]] | accessdate=January 23, 2019}}</ref> and the later [[Jefferson Highway]]<ref>{{cite web |url = https://www.google.com/maps/d/viewer?mid=1kDNFO6G72Zs6uYHw8OoQTF-x5ALIx4xe&ll=36.272239108052105%2C-95.15108052080575&z=11 | title= Jefferson Highway Map | publisher=2lanetraveler.com | accessdate=January 23, 2019}}</ref> of the early [[National Trail System]], both roughly along the route of [[U.S. Route 69 in Oklahoma|U.S. Route 69 through Oklahoma]] today. The town began as a small community at the intersection of the [[Missouri-Kansas-Texas]] (MKT) Railway and the Kansas and Arkansas Valley Railway (a branch of the [[Missouri Pacific Railway]]), when William McAnally, a foreman for the MKT built a small hotel at this isolated location in June 1887. By the next summer others had built two more hotels and two general stores. The town was named for railroad dispatcher Henry \"Big Foot\" Wagoner, who had reported the need for a railroad switch nearby to accommodate the shipment of logs and hay. The switch had been previously named \"Wagoner's Switch.\" The switch soon relocated to the town and caused the development of a major cattle shipping business.<ref name = \"EOHC-Wagoner\"/>\n\nBy 1894, the community had 642 names in a local census. A local newspaper began promoting the town in 1895, encouraging more people to move to there. By 1896, there were approximately 1,500 residents. In the fall of 1895, the community formed a commission that circulated a petition requesting incorporation under the statutes of Arkansas. Incorporation was granted by the U. S. District Court on January 4, 1896, making Wagoner the first city incorporated in Indian Territory.<ref name = \"EOHC-Wagoner\"/>\n\nA privately funded courthouse was built in 1897, which housed a newly created U. S. Western District Court. The [[Dawes Commission]] turned Indian Territory land from tribal to individual ownership by members of each tribe. The individuals were allowed to sell their land to non-Indians, causing a real estate boom in farmland around the area. By statehood, the city had 2,950 residents and was named as the county seat of Wagoner County.<ref name = \"EOHC-Wagoner\"/>\n\nIn April 1914 Wagner was the location of a brutal lynching of a 17 year old colored girl and her parents.  The paper reported that two half-drunken white men walked into her home during the absence of the mother and found the girl dressing.  The men locked themselves into her room and criminally assaulted her.  Her screams for help were heard by her brother, who, kicking down the door, went to her rescue.  In defending his sister, he shot one of the brutes.  The other escaped.  Later in the evening the local authorities, failing to find the brother, arrested the sister, who was taken from jail buy a mob at 4 o'clock in the morning and lynched.  From his hiding place the brother, who is 21 years old, could hear his sister's cries for help, but was powerless to aid her.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Ginzburg |first1=Ralph |title=100 Years of Lynchings |url=https://archive.org/details/100yearsoflynchi00ralp |url-access=registration |date=1988 |publisher=Black Classic Press |location=Baltimore, MD |isbn= 978-0-933121-18-8 |page=[https://archive.org/details/100yearsoflynchi00ralp/page/90 90]}}</ref>\n\nThe boom continued through 1910, when the population reached 4,018. The MKT had located a division headquarters in the city, which then had three railroad trunk lines and twenty passenger trains a day. Industries included three grain elevators, a cotton gin, cotton oil mill, iron foundry, hardwood company, cement plant, and roller mill. However, the boom ended in 1913, when the MKT moved its division headquarters to Muskogee. The oil boom farther west and later, the Great Depression, caused a further decline in the city's economy and population.<ref name = \"EOHC-Wagoner\"/>\n\nWorld War II started a revival of Wagoner's fortunes. The city lay between two war-related Federal Government projects: [[Camp Gruber]] to the south and the [[Oklahoma Ordnance Works]] to the north.<ref name = \"EOHC-Wagoner\"/>\n\nAfter the war, several small manufacturing industries took root. Completion of the nearby [[Fort Gibson Lake]] in 1950 stimulated the economy and turned Wagoner into a sports and retirement center. The McLellan-Kerr navigational channel made the agricultural area accessible by barges, stimulating farm-related businesses. Highway improvements made Wagoner a bedroom community for Tulsa and Muskogee.<ref name = \"EOHC-Wagoner\"/>\n\n==Geography==\nWagoner is located at {{coord|35|57|20|N|95|22|41|W|type:city}} (35.955501, -95.377938).<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/gazette.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2011-04-23|date=2011-02-12|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref> It is {{convert|18|mi|km}} north of [[Muskogee, Oklahoma]] and {{convert|40|mi|km}} east of [[Tulsa]].<ref name = \"EOHC-Wagoner\"/>\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of {{convert|7.0|sqmi|km2}}, all of it land.\n\n==Demographics==\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\" /> of 2000, there were 7,669 people, 2,928 households, and 2,111 families residing in the city. The [[population density]] was 1,101.4 people per square mile (425.4/km\u00b2). There were 3,152 housing units at an average density of 452.7 per square mile (174.9/km\u00b2). The racial makeup of the city was 70.48% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 9.27% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 13.21% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 0.34% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.08% [[Pacific Islander (U.S. Census)|Pacific Islander]], 0.70% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 5.92% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 1.93% of the population.\n\nThere were 2,928 households out of which 35.6% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 52.3% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 15.6% had a female householder with no husband present, and 27.9% were non-families. 25.1% of all households were made up of individuals and 13.1% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.58 and the average family size was 3.06.\n\nIn the city, the population was spread out with 28.1% under the age of 18, 9.9% from 18 to 24, 26.3% from 25 to 44, 21.0% from 45 to 64, and 14.7% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 35 years. For every 100 females, there were 88.7 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 84.7 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the city was $30,493, and the median income for a family was $35,426. Males had a median income of $28,163 versus $21,331 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the city was $14,178. About 12.2% of families and 15.5% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 20.2% of those under age 18 and 14.5% of those age 65 or over.\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[Image:Wagoner Train.jpg|thumb|255px|right|Steamengine train in Wagoner, February 11, 2005]] -->\n\n==Media==\nWagoner has one newspaper, the ''[http://wagonertribune.com American-Tribune]''. The paper is published every Wednesday. It was owned by Community Publishers, a newspaper and Internet publisher and commercial printer that serves Oklahoma, Missouri, and Arkansas.\nOn Tuesday, April 21, 2015, The [http://www.tulsaworld.com/ Tulsa World] announced that its parent company [http://www.bhmginc.com/ BH Media], a division of [http://www.berkshirehathaway.com/ Berkshire Hathaway], the Omaha-based investment holding company led by billionaire [[Warren Buffett]] had purchased several suburban newspapers, including the Wagoner Tribune.<ref>http://www.tulsaworld.com/business/employment/bh-media-group-buys-local-weeklies-tulsa-business-and-legal/article_3981761a-b40c-5fd3-8759-4898875c2e3f.html</ref><ref>http://www.tulsaworld.com/opinion/editorials/tulsa-world-editorial-seven-local-newspapers-join-bh-media-family/article_dad541fd-9898-5de3-864e-23b818d6538d.html</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n* [[Bob Bogle]] (1934-2009), a founding member of [[The Ventures]]\n* [[Shelby Grant]] (1937-2011), actress.<ref name=tulsa>{{cite news|first=Tim|last=Stanley|title=Actress from Wagoner led life of fame, philanthropy |url=http://www.tulsaworld.com/ourlives/article.aspx?subjectid=58&articleid=20110702_11_A19_CUTLIN810932&allcom=1 |work=[[Tulsa World]] |date=2011-07-02|accessdate=2011-07-07}}</ref>\n* [[Willis Hudlin]] (1906-2002), major league baseball pitcher.\n* [[Albert C. Hunt]] (1888-1956), politician, attorney, served as Wagoner City Attorney 1909-1959; later became Justice of Oklahoma Supreme Court\n* [[Bobby Lane]] (born 1939), American football player\n* [[Thomas Sleeper]], (b. 1956) conductor and composer\n<!-- *** INSTRUCTIONS FOR NOTABLE PEOPLE SECTIONS ***\nWhen you add a name in this section, it's YOUR responsibility to ensure all of the following for each person:\n 1) Insert person into list sorted by last name (surname).\n 2) Each person MUST meet [[Wikipedia:Bio]] requirements to ensure notability (see [[Wikipedia:Notability]]).\n 3) Each person MUST meet [[Wikipedia:Verifiability]] requirements to verify their notability and prove they resided in the city.\n 4) If the person has a Wikipedia article, then wikilink the persons name to the correct wikipedia article, otherwise add citation reference(s) to prove the above requirements (see [[Wikipedia:Citing sources]]).\n*** END OF INSTRUCTIONS *** -->\n\n==See also==\n*[[Wagoner High School]]\n*[[Destiny Christian Academy]]\n*[[Wagoner Armory]]\n*[[Cobb Building (Wagoner, Oklahoma)|Cobb Building]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.thecityofwagoner.org/ Wagoner Chamber of Commerce]\n* [http://www.wagoner.lib.ok.us/ Wagoner Public Library]\n* [http://www.wagonerps.org/ Wagoner Public Schools]\n\n{{Tulsa metro}}\n{{Wagoner County, Oklahoma}}\n{{Oklahoma county seats}}\n{{NRHP in Wagoner County}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cities in Wagoner County, Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Cities in Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:County seats in Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Tulsa metropolitan area]]\n[[Category:1887 establishments in Indian Territory]]\n", "name_user": "Stolid99one1a", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:changed 'Wagner' to Wagoner; changed 'colored girl' to African American girl; changed 'buy her brother' to 'by her brother'; changed 'is 21' to 'was 21'", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wagoner,_Oklahoma"}
{"title_page": "Castle of Evoramonte", "text_new": "{{Infobox military installation\n| name            = Castle of Evoramonte\n| ensign          = \n| ensign_size     =\n| native_name     = Castelo de Evoramonte\n| type            = Castle\n<!-- images -->\n| image           = EvoramonteView.jpg\n| caption         = The smooth surfaces of the castle of Evoramonte visible on the approach to the structure\n<!-- maps and coordinates -->\n| map                   = {{Infobox mapframe|id=Q2043483|zoom=13|frame-width=300}}\n| image_map             = \n| map_caption           = Location of the castle within the municipality of [[Estremoz Municipality|Estremoz]]\n| pushpin_map           = \n| pushpin_relief        = \n| pushpin_map_caption   =  \n| coordinates           = {{coord|38.7718312|-7.7158236|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| coordinates_footnotes = \n<!-- location -->\n| partof           = \n| location         = [[\u00c9vora District|\u00c9vora]], [[Alentejo Central]], [[Alentejo]]\n| nearest_town     = \n| country          = [[Portugal]]\n<!-- stats -->\n| ownership        = Portuguese Republic\n| operator         = DRC Alentejo (Dispatch 829/2009; [[Di\u00e1rio da Rep\u00fablica|DR]], S\u00e9rie 2 (163), 24 August 2009\n| open_to_public   = Public\n| site_area        = \n| built            = 12th Century\n| used             = \n| builder          = \n| materials        = Stone, Granite, Marble\n| height           = \n| length           = \n| fate             = \n| condition        = \n| battles          = \n| events           = \n| garrison         = \n| occupants        = \n| website          = \n| footnotes        = \n}}\nThe '''Castle of Evoramonte''', alternately spelled ''\u00c9vora Monte'' or ''\u00c9voramonte'', ({{lang-pt|Castelo de \u00c9vora Monte/Castelo de Evoramonte|links=no}}) is a Portuguese [[Castles in Portugal|castle]] in the [[Freguesia (Portugal)|civil parish]] of [[Evoramonte]], municipality of [[Estremoz Municipality|Estremoz]] in the former district of [[\u00c9vora (district)|\u00c9vora]]. Initiated in 1160, in the [[Gothic architecture|Gothic]] period, it was enlarged in later centuries in the [[Manueline]] style. It was at this site that the [[Concession of Evoramonte]] (or the ''Convention of Evoramonte'') on was signed on 26 May 1834, that ended [[Liberal Wars]] between the Liberal forces of Queen [[Maria II of Portugal]] (under the regency of her father [[Pedro I of Brazil|Peter VI of Portugal]]) and Absolutist armies of [[Miguel of Portugal]].<ref>David Birmingham (1993)</ref> Since 1910, it has been listed as a Portuguese [[Monuments of Portugal#National monuments|National monument]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:Evora-Monte.jpg|thumb|170px|left|An engraving from 1684, depicting the walled town of Evoramonte, with the tower in the centre]]\n[[File:Castelo evoramonte 1.jpg|thumb|170px|left|The imposing and sobre surfaces of the Castle of Evoramonte]]\nSometime during the 12th century, the region of \u00c9vora Monte was conquered from the Moors by the forces of [[Geraldo Sem Pavor]].<ref name=\"SIPA\">{{citation |url=http://www.monumentos.pt/Site/APP_PagesUser/SIPA.aspx?id=2720 |title=Castelo de \u00c9vora Monte/Castelo de Evoramonte (PT040704040002) |publisher=SIPA\u2013Sistema de Informa\u00e7\u00e3o para o Patrim\u00f3nio Arquitect\u00f3nico |editor=SIPA |location=Lisbon, Portugal |language=Portuguese |first=Manuel |last=Branco |year=1993 |accessdate=28 December 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130813083742/http://www.monumentos.pt/Site/APP_PagesUser/SIPA.aspx?id=2720 |archivedate=13 August 2013 }}</ref><ref name=\"IGESPAR\">{{cite web |url=http://www.igespar.pt/en/patrimonio/pesquisa/geral/patrimonioimovel/detail/70670/ |title=Castelo de \u00c9voramonte |editor=IGESPAR |accessdate=27 December 2012 |year=2011 |location=Lisbon, Portugal |publisher=IGESPAR-Instituto de Gest\u00e3o do Patrim\u00f3nio Arquitect\u00f3nico e Arqueol\u00f3gico |language=Portuguese |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120317130015/http://www.igespar.pt/en/patrimonio/pesquisa/geral/patrimonioimovel/detail/70670/ |archivedate=17 March 2012 }}</ref> By 1248, a [[foral]] (''charter'') was issued to the region to provide incentives for settlement, which was reaffirmed in 1271.<ref name=SIPA/><ref name=IGESPAR/>\n\nAround 1306, King [[Denis of Portugal|Denis]] ordered the fortification of the town: it was at this time that construction of the castle began, that included the main structure, walls and gates.<ref name=SIPA/><ref name=IGESPAR/>\n\nAfter the rise of [[John I of Portugal]] to the Portuguese throne, the castle and associated lands were given to the constable [[Nuno \u00c1lvares Pereira]], who later passed them on to his grandson.\n\nA new foral was issued in 1516, by King [[Manuel I of Portugal|Manuel]].<ref name=SIPA/><ref name=IGESPAR/> The reconstruction campaign during Manuel's reign, beginning in 1516, resulted in the fortification with four cylindrical towers defining the rectangular perimeter by Francisco de Arruda (completed in 1531).<ref name=IGESPAR/>\n\nThe [[1531 Lisbon earthquake]] destroyed the keep tower of the medieval castle. This structure was then rebuilt by [[Teod\u00f3sio I, Duke of Braganza]], who, at that time, was master of the region and town.<ref name=SIPA/>\n\nOn 26 May 1834, the [[Concession of Evoramonte]] was signed between [[Miguel of Portugal]] and his brother [[Pedro I of Brazil|Peter VI of Portugal]], in the name of his daughter [[Maria II of Portugal|Maria da Gl\u00f3ria]], ending the [[Liberal Wars]].<ref name=SIPA/>\n\nIn 1855 the municipality of Evoramonte was extinguished, and its historical administration divided into the neighbouring municipalities of [[Estremoz Municipality|Estremoz]], [[\u00c9vora Municipality|\u00c9vora]], [[Arraiolos Municipality|Arraiolos]] and [[Redondo Municipality|Redondo]].<ref name=SIPA/><ref name=IGESPAR/>\n\nBetween 1930 and 1940, were the first public works to recuperate and renovate the grounds and castle of Evoramonte, under the supervision of the ''Direc\u00e7\u00e3o Geral dos Edif\u00edcios e Monumentos Nacionais'' (DGMEN).<ref name=SIPA/><ref name=IGESPAR/> These actions, which primarily occurred in 1937, included the restoration of the towers and the consolidation of the parapets.<ref name=SIPA/>\n\nSubsequent interventions occurred between 1971-1979, in projects to restore the castle; 1980-1981, in the recuperation of the walls; in 1982, the construction of a sanitation system; followed in 1984 by new restoration projects, culminating in the phase two project in 1986 (which included construction and restoration accompanied with photography of the repairs).<ref name=SIPA/> Finally in 1987, electricity was installed on the grounds.<ref name=SIPA/>\n\nOn 1 June 1992, under Decree 106F/92, this building was transferred into the stewardship of the ''Instituto Portugu\u00eas do Patrim\u00f3nio Arquitect\u00f3nico'' (IPPAR), in order to rehabilitate and monetize the structure.<ref name=SIPA/>\n\nFebruary 2006, marked the beginning of commemorations to celebrate the castle's 700 years of existence.<ref name=SIPA/>\n\n==Architecture==\n[[File:Castelo Medieval de Evoramonte.jpg|thumb|235px|right|The grey granite of the castle peeking from behind the medieval walls of the old city]]\n[[File:Interior do Castelo de Evoramonte - Apr 2011.jpg|thumb|235px|right|The internal lattice of columns and nerves of the second floor room of the castle]]\nThe castle crowns the escarpment of Serra d' Ossa, with a commanding view of the local and distant routes, dominating one of the largest squares in Portugal: the municipality of Estremoz.<ref name=SIPA/>\n\nAn unusual rectangular building, the castle includes circular towers molded into the structure, providing the castle with an aggressive and powerful characteristics.<ref name=SIPA/> The building is much larger at the base, and is chamfered to the height of its three storeys, and crowned by large [[merlon]]s. The three floors are clearly delineated by a ring-shaped cornice at each level, typical of the [[Manueline]] style, these cornices are sculpted into a rope, tied at the frontispiece of the structure.<ref name=SIPA/> At various places along the cylindrical towers are canon emplacements, narrower to the interior, that provide an image that is bellicose and somber.<ref name=SIPA/> On each storey there is a rectangular window, except on the ground floor exposed to the north, where a portico is fixed.<ref name=SIPA/>\n\nIn the large salon on the first floor, the vaulted ovular ceiling is supported by four columns, and raised into a mess of sculpted veins.<ref name=SIPA/> A similar lattice, though smaller, is used in the remaining floors. By the cylindrical towers in the west, a circular staircase provides access to successive floors.<ref name=SIPA/>\n\n==References==\n;Notes\n{{Reflist|2}}\n;Sources\n* {{citation |first=David |last=Birmingham |title=Portugal: A concise history |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=1993}}\n* {{citation |last=Espanca |first=T\u00falio |contribution=A Cerca e o Castelo de \u00c9vora Monte |title=A Cidade de \u00c9vora |issue=51\u201352 |year=1962 |language=Portuguese}}\n* {{citation |last=Espanca |first=T\u00falio |title=Invent\u00e1rio Art\u00edstico de Portugal |publisher=Distrito de \u00c9vora |location=Lisbon, Portugal |year=1966 |language=Portuguese}}\n* {{citation |last=PINA |first=Maria do Carmo |title=\u00c9voramonte: A Fortaleza Monografia |location=Lisbon, Portugal |year=1989 |language=Portuguese}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100201012349/http://www.fotopedia.com/en/%C3%89voramonte_Castle Evoramonte Castle gallery] at Fotopedia\n{{Castles in Portugal}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Evoramonte Castle}}\n[[Category:Castles in Portugal|Evoramonte]]\n[[Category:Manueline architecture]]\n[[Category:Gothic architecture in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Castles in \u00c9vora District|Evoramonte]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military installation\n| name            = Castle of Evoramonte\n| ensign          = \n| ensign_size     =\n| native_name     = Castelo de Evoramonte\n| type            = Castle\n<!-- images -->\n| image           = EvoramonteView.jpg\n| caption         = The smooth surfaces of the castle of Evoramonte visible on the approach to the structure\n<!-- maps and coordinates -->\n| map                   = {{Infobox mapframe|id=Q2043483|zoom=13|frame-width=300}}\n| image_map             = \n| map_caption           = Location of the castle within the municipality of [[Estremoz Municipality|Estremoz]]\n| pushpin_map           = \n| pushpin_relief        = \n| pushpin_map_caption   =  \n| coordinates           = {{coord|38.7718312|-7.7158236|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| coordinates_footnotes = \n<!-- location -->\n| partof           = \n| location         = [[\u00c9vora District|\u00c9vora]], [[Alentejo Central]], [[Alentejo]]\n| nearest_town     = \n| country          = [[Portugal]]\n<!-- stats -->\n| ownership        = Portuguese Republic\n| operator         = DRC Alentejo (Dispatch 829/2009; [[Di\u00e1rio da Rep\u00fablica|DR]], S\u00e9rie 2 (163), 24 August 2009\n| open_to_public   = Public\n| site_area        = \n| built            = 12th Century\n| used             = \n| builder          = \n| materials        = Stone, Granite, Marble\n| height           = \n| length           = \n| fate             = \n| condition        = \n| battles          = \n| events           = \n| garrison         = \n| occupants        = \n| website          = \n| footnotes        = \n}}\nThe '''Castle of Evoramonte''', alternately spelled ''\u00c9vora Monte'' or ''\u00c9voramonte'', ({{lang-pt|Castelo de \u00c9vora Monte/Castelo de Evoramonte|links=no}}) is a Portuguese [[Castles in Portugal|castle]] in the [[Freguesia (Portugal)|civil parish]] of [[Evoramonte]], municipality of [[Estremoz Municipality|Estremoz]] in the former district of [[\u00c9vora (district)|\u00c9vora]]. Initiated in 1160, in the [[Gothic architecture|Gothic]] period, it was enlarged in later centuries in the [[Manueline]] style. It was at this site that the [[Concession of Evoramonte]] (or the ''Convention of Evoramonte'') on was signed on 26 May 1834, that ended [[Liberal Wars]] between the Liberal forces of Queen [[Maria II of Portugal]] (under the regency of her father [[Pedro I of Brazil|Peter VI of Portugal]]) and Absolutist armies of [[Miguel of Portugal]].<ref>David Birmingham (1993)</ref> Since 1910, it has been listed as a Portuguese [[Monuments of Portugal#National monuments|National monument]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:Evora-Monte.jpg|thumb|170px|left|An engraving from 1684, depicting the walled town of Evoramonte, with the tower in the centre]]\n[[File:Castelo evoramonte 1.jpg|thumb|170px|left|The imposing and sobre surfaces of the Castle of Evoramonte, in reality]]\nSometime during the 12th century, the region of \u00c9vora Monte was conquered from the Moors by the forces of [[Geraldo Sem Pavor]].<ref name=\"SIPA\">{{citation |url=http://www.monumentos.pt/Site/APP_PagesUser/SIPA.aspx?id=2720 |title=Castelo de \u00c9vora Monte/Castelo de Evoramonte (PT040704040002) |publisher=SIPA\u2013Sistema de Informa\u00e7\u00e3o para o Patrim\u00f3nio Arquitect\u00f3nico |editor=SIPA |location=Lisbon, Portugal |language=Portuguese |first=Manuel |last=Branco |year=1993 |accessdate=28 December 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130813083742/http://www.monumentos.pt/Site/APP_PagesUser/SIPA.aspx?id=2720 |archivedate=13 August 2013 }}</ref><ref name=\"IGESPAR\">{{cite web |url=http://www.igespar.pt/en/patrimonio/pesquisa/geral/patrimonioimovel/detail/70670/ |title=Castelo de \u00c9voramonte |editor=IGESPAR |accessdate=27 December 2012 |year=2011 |location=Lisbon, Portugal |publisher=IGESPAR-Instituto de Gest\u00e3o do Patrim\u00f3nio Arquitect\u00f3nico e Arqueol\u00f3gico |language=Portuguese |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120317130015/http://www.igespar.pt/en/patrimonio/pesquisa/geral/patrimonioimovel/detail/70670/ |archivedate=17 March 2012 }}</ref> By 1248, a [[foral]] (''charter'') was issued to the region to provide incentives for settlement, which was reaffirmed in 1271.<ref name=SIPA/><ref name=IGESPAR/>\n\nAround 1306, King [[Denis of Portugal|Denis]] ordered the fortification of the town: it was at this time that construction of the castle began, that included the main structure, walls and gates.<ref name=SIPA/><ref name=IGESPAR/>\n\nAfter the rise of [[John I of Portugal]] to the Portuguese throne, the castle and associated lands were given to the constable [[Nuno \u00c1lvares Pereira]], who later passed them on to his grandson.\n\nA new foral was issued in 1516, by King [[Manuel I of Portugal|Manuel]].<ref name=SIPA/><ref name=IGESPAR/> The reconstruction campaign during Manuel's reign, beginning in 1516, resulted in the fortification with four cylindrical towers defining the rectangular perimeter by Francisco de Arruda (completed in 1531).<ref name=IGESPAR/>\n\nThe [[1531 Lisbon earthquake]] destroyed the keep tower of the medieval castle. This structure was then rebuilt by [[Teod\u00f3sio I, Duke of Braganza]], who, at that time, was master of the region and town.<ref name=SIPA/>\n\nOn 26 May 1834, the [[Concession of Evoramonte]] was signed between [[Miguel of Portugal]] and his brother [[Pedro I of Brazil|Peter VI of Portugal]], in the name of his daughter [[Maria II of Portugal|Maria da Gl\u00f3ria]], ending the [[Liberal Wars]].<ref name=SIPA/>\n\nIn 1855 the municipality of Evoramonte was extinguished, and its historical administration divided into the neighbouring municipalities of [[Estremoz Municipality|Estremoz]], [[\u00c9vora Municipality|\u00c9vora]], [[Arraiolos Municipality|Arraiolos]] and [[Redondo Municipality|Redondo]].<ref name=SIPA/><ref name=IGESPAR/>\n\nBetween 1930 and 1940, were the first public works to recuperate and renovate the grounds and castle of Evoramonte, under the supervision of the ''Direc\u00e7\u00e3o Geral dos Edif\u00edcios e Monumentos Nacionais'' (DGMEN).<ref name=SIPA/><ref name=IGESPAR/> These actions, which primarily occurred in 1937, included the restoration of the towers and the consolidation of the parapets.<ref name=SIPA/>\n\nSubsequent interventions occurred between 1971-1979, in projects to restore the castle; 1980-1981, in the recuperation of the walls; in 1982, the construction of a sanitation system; followed in 1984 by new restoration projects, culminating in the phase two project in 1986 (which included construction and restoration accompanied with photography of the repairs).<ref name=SIPA/> Finally in 1987, electricity was installed on the grounds.<ref name=SIPA/>\n\nOn 1 June 1992, under Decree 106F/92, this building was transferred into the stewardship of the ''Instituto Portugu\u00eas do Patrim\u00f3nio Arquitect\u00f3nico'' (IPPAR), in order to rehabilitate and monetize the structure.<ref name=SIPA/>\n\nFebruary 2006, marked the beginning of commemorations to celebrate the castle's 700 years of existence.<ref name=SIPA/>\n\n==Architecture==\n[[File:Castelo Medieval de Evoramonte.jpg|thumb|235px|right|The grey granite of the castle peeking from behind the medieval walls of the old city]]\n[[File:Interior do Castelo de Evoramonte - Apr 2011.jpg|thumb|235px|right|The internal lattice of columns and nerves of the second floor room of the castle]]\nThe castle crowns the escarpment of Serra d' Ossa, with a commanding view of the local and distant routes, dominating one of the largest squares in Portugal: the municipality of Estremoz.<ref name=SIPA/>\n\nAn unusual rectangular building, the castle includes circular towers molded into the structure, providing the castle with an aggressive and powerful characteristics.<ref name=SIPA/> The building is much larger at the base, and is chamfered to the height of its three storeys, and crowned by large [[merlon]]s. The three floors are clearly delineated by a ring-shaped cornice at each level, typical of the [[Manueline]] style, these cornices are sculpted into a rope, tied at the frontispiece of the structure.<ref name=SIPA/> At various places along the cylindrical towers are canon emplacements, narrower to the interior, that provide an image that is bellicose and somber.<ref name=SIPA/> On each storey there is a rectangular window, except on the ground floor exposed to the north, where a portico is fixed.<ref name=SIPA/>\n\nIn the large salon on the first floor, the vaulted ovular ceiling is supported by four columns, and raised into a mess of sculpted veins.<ref name=SIPA/> A similar lattice, though smaller, is used in the remaining floors. By the cylindrical towers in the west, a circular staircase provides access to successive floors.<ref name=SIPA/>\n\n==References==\n;Notes\n{{Reflist|2}}\n;Sources\n* {{citation |first=David |last=Birmingham |title=Portugal: A concise history |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=1993}}\n* {{citation |last=Espanca |first=T\u00falio |contribution=A Cerca e o Castelo de \u00c9vora Monte |title=A Cidade de \u00c9vora |issue=51\u201352 |year=1962 |language=Portuguese}}\n* {{citation |last=Espanca |first=T\u00falio |title=Invent\u00e1rio Art\u00edstico de Portugal |publisher=Distrito de \u00c9vora |location=Lisbon, Portugal |year=1966 |language=Portuguese}}\n* {{citation |last=PINA |first=Maria do Carmo |title=\u00c9voramonte: A Fortaleza Monografia |location=Lisbon, Portugal |year=1989 |language=Portuguese}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100201012349/http://www.fotopedia.com/en/%C3%89voramonte_Castle Evoramonte Castle gallery] at Fotopedia\n{{Castles in Portugal}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Evoramonte Castle}}\n[[Category:Castles in Portugal|Evoramonte]]\n[[Category:Manueline architecture]]\n[[Category:Gothic architecture in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Castles in \u00c9vora District|Evoramonte]]\n", "name_user": "RetiredDuke", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:yes, it's a photo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Castle_of_Evoramonte"}
{"title_page": "Bones (season 2)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox television season\n |season_number = 2\n |image = [[File:Bones-s2-dvd.jpg]]\n |caption = Season 2 DVD cover art\n |bgcolour = #000000\n |country = United States\n |network = [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]\n |first_aired = {{Start date|2006|8|30}}\n |last_aired = {{End date|2007|5|16}}\n |num_episodes = 21\n |episode_list = List of Bones episodes\n}}\nThe second season of the American television series ''[[Bones (TV series)|Bones]]'' premiered on August 30, 2006, and concluded on May 16, 2007, on [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]. The show aired on Wednesdays at 8:00 pm ET for the entire season and consisted of 21 episodes. The season averaged 9.4 million viewers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allbusiness.com/entertainment-arts/broadcasting-industry/6626343-1.html |title=2006-07 primetime wrap|work=Hollywood Reporter |date=May 25, 2007 |accessdate=April 2, 2010}}</ref>\n\n== Cast and characters ==\n{{See also|List of Bones characters}}\n\n=== Main cast ===\nTamara Taylor joined the cast this season after the departure of [[Jonathan Adams (American actor)|Jonathan Adams]]. Taylor first appeared in the first six episodes of the season as a guest star and was promoted to a series regular and appeared in the opening credits beginning with episode 7.\n* [[Emily Deschanel]] as [[Temperance \"Bones\" Brennan|Dr. Temperance \"Bones\" Brennan]], a [[forensic anthropologist]]\n* [[David Boreanaz]] as FBI Special Agent [[Seeley Booth]], the official FBI liaison with the Jeffersonian\n* [[Michaela Conlin]] as [[Angela Montenegro]], a [[forensic artist]]\n* [[Eric Millegan]] as [[Zack Addy|Dr. Zack Addy]], Dr. Brennan's lab assistant and now a professional forensic anthropologist\n* [[T. J. Thyne]] as [[Jack Hodgins (Bones)|Dr. Jack Hodgins]], an [[entomologist]]\n* [[Tamara Taylor]] as [[Camille Saroyan|Dr. Camille Saroyan]], a [[forensic pathologist]] and the new head of the forensic division\n\n=== Recurring cast ===\n* [[Eddie McClintock]] as [[List of Bones characters#Tim Sullivan|Tim \"Sully\" Sullivan]]\n* [[Patricia Belcher]] as [[List of Bones characters#Caroline Julian|Caroline Julian]], a prosecutor\n* [[Stephen Fry]] as Dr. [[List of Bones characters#Gordon Wyatt|Gordon Wyatt]], Booth's psychiatrist who evaluates his behavior\n* Nathan Dean as FBI Special Agent [[List of Bones characters#Charlie Burns|Charlie Burns]]\n* [[Ryan O'Neal]] as [[List of Bones characters#Matthew Brennan / Max Keenan|Max Keenan]], Brennan's fugitive father\n* [[Jessica Capshaw]] as [[List of Bones characters#Rebecca Stinson|Rebecca Stinson]], Booth's ex-girlfriend and Parker's mother\n* Heath Freeman as [[List of Bones characters#Howard Epps|Howard Epps]], a serial killer\n* [[Ty Panitz]] as [[List of Bones characters#Parker Booth|Parker Booth]], Booth's son\n* Chris Conner as [[List of Bones characters#Oliver Laurier|Oliver Laurier]]\n* [[Loren Dean]] as [[List of Bones characters#Russ Brennan|Russ Brennan]], Brennan's brother\n* [[Billy Gibbons]] as Angela's father\n* [[David Greenman]] as [[List of Bones characters#Marcus Geier|Marcus Geier]], a forensic technician\n* [[Danny Woodburn]] as [[List of Bones characters#Alex Radziwill|Alex Radziwill]], a Diplomatic immunity and State Department official\n\n== Episodes ==\nThe episode \"[[Bones (season 3)#ep54|Player Under Pressure]]\" was originally supposed to air in April 2007 as episode 19, but was delayed in the wake of the [[Virginia Tech massacre]], as the episode's plot featured finding human remains on a college campus.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ca.eonline.com/uberblog/b54918_fox_pulls_bones_in_wake_of_college.html | title =Fox Pulls Bones in Wake of College Massacre |work=E! Online |date=April 17, 2007 |accessdate=April 2, 2010}}</ref> The episode later aired in April 2008 as part of the third season, with new footage. The episode \"Aliens in a Spaceship\" introduces the storyline of the Grave Digger, an unresolved case. The Grave Digger would later return in the [[Bones (season 4)|fourth season]], when the team discovers its identity. Serial killer [[Howard Epps]] returns for two episodes, in which the team must discover more of his victims.\n<onlyinclude>{{Episode table\n|background  = #000000\n|overall     = 6\n|season      = 6\n|title       = 23\n|director    = 14\n|writer      = 19\n|airdate     = 16\n|prodcode    = 6\n|viewers     = 10\n|country     = US\n|episodes    = \n{{Episode list/sublist|Bones (season 2)\n |MainList=List of Bones episodes\n |EpisodeNumber=23\n |EpisodeNumber2=1\n |Title=[[The Titan on the Tracks]]\n |WrittenBy=[[Hart Hanson]]\n |DirectedBy=[[Tony Wharmby]]\n |Viewers=8.61<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcmedianet.com/web/dnr/dispDNR.aspx?id=090606_05|title=Weekly Program Rankings|work=ABC Medianet|date=September 6, 2006|accessdate=December 17, 2012}}</ref>\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|2006|8|30}}\n |ProdCode=2AKY01\n |ShortSummary=Brennan and Booth investigate the site of a train wreck where the bodies of a senator and a high-profile businessman are found within the wreckage. The businessman's body is found in a car on the train tracks, and at first look, it is an apparent suicide. While investigating a possible connection between the two victims, Brennan and her team discover the businessman is still alive, but severely injured, at a local hospital, and the body at the scene is someone else. As the clues begin to unravel, the investigation gets more complicated when details of the man's private life are revealed, leading Brennan and Booth to a private detective who may hold key information. Meanwhile, Brennan is introduced to Dr. Camille Saroyan, a first-rate pathologist who has been hired as the head of forensics at the Jeffersonian, and more importantly, Brennan's boss. It doesn't take long for Brennan to figure out \"Cam\" is a little too familiar with Booth and they share something of a past. Also, Booth encourages Brennan to visit her mother's grave site for the first time.\n |LineColor=000000\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|Bones (season 2)\n |MainList=List of Bones episodes\n |EpisodeNumber=24\n |EpisodeNumber2=2\n |Title=Mother and Child in the Bay\n |WrittenBy=Stephen Nathan\n |DirectedBy=[[Jes\u00fas Salvador Trevi\u00f1o|Jes\u00fas Trevi\u00f1o]]\n |Viewers=9.13<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcmedianet.com/web/dnr/dispDNR.aspx?id=091206_11 |title=Weekly Program Rankings |work=ABC Medianet |date=September 12, 2006 |accessdate=December 17, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120329105539/http://abcmedianet.com/web/dnr/dispDNR.aspx?id=091206_11 |archivedate=March 29, 2012 }}</ref>\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|2006|9|6}}\n |ProdCode=2AKY02\n |ShortSummary=Booth and Brennan investigate the remains of a woman and unborn baby washed up on the beach of the Delaware Bay. The body is identified as that of Carlie Richardson, a pregnant newly-wed whose mysterious disappearance one year ago had been a major national news story. However, the immediate prime suspect, Richardson's husband, has also disappeared. Meanwhile, Booth is annoyed his ex-girlfriend Rebecca, the mother of his son Parker, is letting Parker spend so much time with her new boyfriend.\n |LineColor=000000\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|Bones (season 2)\n |MainList=List of Bones episodes\n |EpisodeNumber=25\n |EpisodeNumber2=3\n |Title=The Boy in the Shroud\n |WrittenBy=[[Gary Glasberg]]\n |DirectedBy=[[Sanford Bookstaver]]\n |Viewers=8.59<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcmedianet.com/web/dnr/dispDNR.aspx?id=091906_03|title=Weekly Program Rankings|work=ABC Medianet|date=September 19, 2006|accessdate=December 17, 2012}}</ref>\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|2006|9|13}}\n |ProdCode=2AKY03\n |ShortSummary=Brennan and her team dig through the trash to find clues when a young man wrapped in a shroud is found among garbage. After Angela is able to identify the deceased boy, Cam quickly assumes the main suspect to be